1. Commenting on variable declarations

When you declare a new variable, it's helpful to include a comment describing what the variable represents. For example:

```
// Declare a variable to hold the user's name
let userName = "John";
```

This comment helps anyone reading your code to quickly understand the purpose of the variable. 2. Commenting on function definitions

When you define a new function, it's helpful to include a comment explaining what the function does, along with any relevant parameters or return values. For example:

```
// This function calculates the sum of two numbers
function sum(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}
```

This comment helps anyone reading your code to understand the purpose of the function and how to use it. 3. Commenting on complex code blocks

If you have a complex block of code that might be difficult to understand at first glance, it's helpful to include a comment explaining what the code is doing. For example:

```
// Check if the user is logged in and has permission to view this page
if (user.isLoggedIn() && user.hasPermission("viewPage")) {
  // Display the page contents
  showPageContents();
} else {
  // Redirect to the login page
  redirectToLoginPage();
}
```

This comment helps anyone reading your code to quickly understand the logic behind the code block. 4. Commenting as you write code

As you write your code, it's helpful to comment on what you're doing in real-time. This can help you keep organized and make it easier to come back to the code later. For example:

```
// Define an array to hold the current user's shopping cart items
let cartItems = [];

// Loop through all available products
for (let product of allProducts) {
